<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Program To Provide Work for Surplus Rural Workers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0502153094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1449 GMT 5 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0502153094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, February 5 (XINHUA) -- China is drawing up 
a "rural-urban coordination employment program" to find work for 
its 130 million surplus rural laborers, the Ministry of Labor 
said today. 
  A pilot scheme of this program will be implemented this year 
in eight provinces, said Vice-Minister of Labor Zhu Jiazhen. 
  The provinces for the try-out are either populous but less 
developed inland provinces such as Sichuan and Anhui, or coastal 
provinces of Guangdong and Jiangsu, which are short of labor 
because of rapid economic development, Zhu said. 
  The scheme focuses on the development of small rural 
industrial districts and rural towns -- enlarging the existing 
ones and establishing new ones -- to take in extra laborers from 
their own regions, he added. 
  The move will also narrow the gap between rural and urban 
areas, said the vice-minister. 
  Other laborers could migrate to more developed coastal 
regions, he said, noting that an inter-provincial labor 
migration plan started last year has achieved initial successes. 
  China now has 130 million surplus rural laborers, and in 
eight years the rural areas will have 70 million new laborers, 
the vice-minister said. 
  The employment program was designed by the Labor Ministry, 
the Agriculture Ministry and the State Council Development and 
Research Center. 

</TEXT>

