<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Utility Firms Banned From Restricting Competition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0902071294 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0628 
GMT 2 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0902071294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Fu Gang (0265 0474)] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, 2 Feb (XINHUA) -- The "Regulations on 
Prohibiting Public Utility Enterprises From Restricting 
Competition," [hereinafter referred to as the "Regulations"] 
which were established by the State Administration for Industry 
and Commerce based on the "PRC Anti-Unfair Competition Law," 
have been promulgated for implementation. 
  Public utility enterprises refer to enterprises dealing in 
public services such as water supply, heat supply, gas supply, 
postal service, telecommunications, and transportation. 
According to the "Regulations," public utility enterprises may 
not use their advantageous positions to obstruct fair 
competition from other businesses, nor are they allowed to 
infringe upon consumers legitimate rights and interests. 
Specifically, public utility enterprises are prohibited from 
taking the following competition-restricting measures: 
  -- Demanding that their clients and consumers can only 
purchase and use relevant commodities provided by them but not 
similar commodities provided by other dealers that meet 
established technical standards; 
  -- Demanding that their clients and consumers can only 
purchase and use relevant commodities produced or sold by 
dealers designated by them but not similar commodities provided 
by other dealers that meet established technical standards; 
  -- Compelling their clients and consumers to purchase 
unnecessary commodities and accessories provided by them and 
unnecessary commodities provided by dealers designated by them; 
  -- Using commodity quality and performance inspections as a 
pretext to obstruct clients and consumers from purchasing and 
using commodities provided by other dealers that meet the 
established technical standards. 
  If a public utility enterprise commits one or more of the 
aforementioned offenses, the concerned industry and commerce 
administration department must order it to stop the practice 
and, according to the seriousness of the case, may impose a fine 
ranging from 50,000 to 200,000 yuan. If a public utility 
enterprise refuses to accept the punishment decision and 
continues its illegal practice, this constitutes a new offense 
and the enterprise in question should be more severely punished. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

