<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Roundup' Views Development of Port Construction </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0702064094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0624 GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0702064094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Roundup": "China Speeds Up Port Construction"] </F>
  [Text] Beijing, February 7 (XINHUA) -- Construction of 
ports in the coastal areas of China is in full swing. 
  So far, China has 300 deepwater berths along its 32,000-km 
coastline, and the total deadweight tonnage of its ocean-going 
ships ranks eighth in the world. 
  According to a plan, more than 100 deep-water berths will be 
added to boost its port handling capacity in 1995. 
  Through years of construction, the country has formed three 
major port groups -- the area around Bohai bay with 40 ports, 
the Chang Jiang river estuary with 20 ports and the southeast 
coastal area with ten ports. 
  Another port group is being formed in Shandong and Jiangsu 
Provinces in the central part of the coastline. 
  A survey shows that the Chang Jiang river estuary has 60 
deep- water berths able to accommodate ships of 10,000 dwt in 
recent years, and the construction of large ports and wharves is 
well under way in the southern coastal areas. 
  By the end of this century China will have some ten ports 
with annual handling capacities exceeding 100 million tons each. 
  While building more ports, China is paying attention to port 
modernization in co-operation with overseas companies. 
  The coastal areas are home to five special economic zones, a 
dozen bonded zones and a number of open coastal cities. 
  The areas around bohai bay have established trade relations 
with 160 countries and regions. 
  As a result, their imports and exports account for more than 
one half of the country's total. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

