<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Clinton Announces Ultimatum on Sarajevo Shelling </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1002003394 Beijing XINHUA in English 2343 GMT 9 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1002003394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, February 9 (XINHUA) -- U.S. President 
Bill Clinton announced here today that NATO has approved an 
ultimatum on the Bosnian Serbs to remove heavy weapons from 
around Sarajevo and stop shelling the Muslims within 10 days. 
  Speaking at a White House press conference, Clinton said 
NATO 
forces "stand ready" to carry out air strikes against "anyone, 
anyone" who further launch shells. 
  NATO made a similar announcement, with more details, in 
Brussels, Belgium, minutes later. 
  Just before the NATO announcement, the Bosnian Serbs and 
Muslims reached a new ceasefire, on top of the numerous ones 
that failed before. 
  Clinton welcomed the move, hoping the latest ceasefire would 
really hold this time. 
  He said Washington has important interest in seeing the end 
of the Bosnian carnage. 
  Although the situation does not justify U.S. unilateral 
actions, it deserves active U.S. efforts and leadership in 
seeking a diplomatic solution to the conflict and otherwise, 
Clinton said. 
  In response to a question on Russia's opposition to the NATO 
air strikes ultimatum, Clinton said attempts earlier today to 
call President Boris Yeltsin had failed and he would try to talk 
to him later. 
  Clinton said he hopes the Russians would at least 
understand, 
if not agree with, the NATO move. 
  Russia has traditional and historical links with the Serbs 
and Clinton stressed that the NATO threat "applies to anyone, 
not only the Serbs." 
  The President said he was grateful for the support of the 
countries with soldiers in Bosnia, such as France, Britain, 
Canada and Spain. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-26595 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi028_b_94002" </HT>


