<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Clinton Hails Israel-PLO Agreement in Cairo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1002054094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0518 GMT 10 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1002054094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, February 9 (XINHUA) -- U.S. President 
Bill Clinton today hailed an agreement by Israel and the 
Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) on implementing a 
declaration of principles for Palestinian self-rule on the West 
Bank and in Gaza. 
  "In Cairo, Foreign Minister Peres and Yasir 'Arafat 
announced 
an agreement on self-rule and on the terms of withdrawal from 
Gaza and Jericho," Clinton told the World Jewish Congress. 
  "I think another big milestone has been achieved today," he 
said. 
  The negotiations in Cairo were designed to implement the 
historic accord signed in Washington last September and setting 
December 13, 1993, for the military pullout of Israel, which 
balked at negotiations over details of the plan for weeks. 
  Clinton said that the U.S. approach is to ensure the 
successful implementation of the declaration of principles and 
will show the Israelis that the agreement can not only enhance 
their security but provide a self-government for their 
Palestinian neighbors. 
  Meanwhile, he described the U.S. commitment to maintaining 
and enhancing the security of Israel as "ironclad" and a 
precondition for a just and lasting peace in the Middle East. 
  "To achieve our goal of a comprehensive settlement," Clinton 
stressed, "we insist that the Arab boycott of Israel end now." 

</TEXT>

