<F P=100> Sub-Saharan Africa </F>
<H3> <TI>   Jiang Zemin Sends Condolences on Ivorian Leader's Death </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0902141194 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1306 
GMT 7 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0902141194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Wang Wencheng (3769 2429 2052)] </F>
  [Text] Yamassoukro, 7 Feb (XINHUA) -- The funeral of the 
late former Ivorian President Felix Houphouet-Biogny, who died 
of illness on 7 December last year, was ceremoniously held in 
the Ivorian political capital of Yamassoukro today. 
  The funeral rites were held in a combination of the 
traditional customs of the Baoule people and the ceremony of a 
modern state funeral. In the morning, the "Biogny Peace 
Foundation Building" was filled with solemn silence, with 
Biogny's bronze coffin well placed in the middle of the mourning 
hall where his portrait was hung. At 1100, the cortege left the 
"Peace Foundation Building" for the "Ave Maria Peace Cathedral" 
for a memorial mass. The remains were later buried at the 
Biogny Tomb within the compound of the Presidential Residence. 
  Leaders and special envoys from over 70 countries, and 
representatives of nearly 40 international and regional 
organizations, attended Biogny's funeral. 
  Chinese President Jiang Zemin sent a condolence cable. Liu 
Chengguo, vice agriculture minister and special envoy of the 
Chinese Government, was all the way here to attend Biogny's 
funeral. 
  Born to the family of a tribal chief in Yamassoukro on 18 
October 1905, Biogny practiced medicine in his early days and 
was president of the Ivory Coast since its independence on 7 
August 1960. He was a pioneer of the African nationality 
independence movements and an influential senior statesman. 

</TEXT>

