<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   French Premier Views NATO Ultimatum To Serbs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1502022694 Beijing XINHUA in English 0159 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1502022694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, February 14 (XINHUA) -- NATO's ultimatum to 
Bosnian warring sides "will not be prolonged for a single day," 
French Prime Minister Edouard Balladur said on Television France 
2 Monday [14 February] evening. 
  On February 9, the 16 countries of the North Atlantic Treaty 
Organization (NATO) passed an ultimatum demanding the warring 
parties in Bosnia to lift the siege of Sarajevo and withdraw or 
put under UN control all the heavy weapons within a 20-kilometer 
range of the city before a 10-day deadline. 
  NATO will launch air strikes on the mortar positions that do 
not respect the ultimatum. 
  Balladur hoped that the Bosnian warring sides would conform 
to NATO's demand and "return to the negotiating table." 
  "If they don't," he stressed, "it goes without saying that 
what has been said will be done." 
  Balladur said that his government was deeply concerned with 
the situation of the French peace-keeping troops in Bosnia, who 
are on an "extremely dangerous" humanitarian mission. 
  He said that the government would "take every measure to 
ensure their security." 
  The latest statistics showed that by February 1 this year, a 
total of 10,760 soldiers of the UN Protection Forces (UNPROFOR) 
were stationed in Bosnia, 4,077 of whom were French. 
  Balladur said that France accounts for the largest share in 
the UNPROFOR but it would be "meaningless" for them to continue 
their presence if the fightings there "should go on for five, 
ten or even 15 years." 

</TEXT>

