<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   XINHUA Reports French UN Envoy's Comments on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1502013794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0127 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1502013794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] United Nations, February 14 (XINHUA) -- France today 
again warned the warring parties in Bosnia to place their heavy 
weapons under UN control, or face air strikes. 
  Speaking at a UN Security Council session on Bosnia, France 
Ambassador to the United Nations, Jean-Bernard Merimee, said 
"the conflict has now reached a turning point, which we should 
all be aware of." 
  Interpreting the NATO decision on Bosnia adopted on February 
9, the ambassador said the decision essentially aimed to have 
heavy weapons placed under UN Protection Force (UNPROFOR) 
control within 10 days, and "those weapons positions that had 
not been withdrawn would be subject to air strikes." 
  He said the decision had the sole aim of providing the 
United 
Nations with the means of implementing the decisions of the 
Security Council. 
  The first priority, he said, was to lift the siege of 
Sarajevo, begin its demilitarization and progress towards 
placing that city under temporary UN administration. 
  The ambassador said France shared the objective put forward 
by Russia on placing Sarajevo under UN administration, but that 
must not interfere with the recent NATO decision. 
  However, he said, his government was fully prepared to 
support all efforts to achieve peace through negotiations, and 
"the time has come for us all to come out in favor of peace." 

</TEXT>

