<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S Says Diplomacy Not Enough To End Bosnian Crisis </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1402234094 Beijing XINHUA in English 2326 GMT 14 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1402234094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] United Nations, February 14 (XINHUA) -- The United 
States said here today that to end the conflicts in Bosnia and 
Herzegovina diplomacy alone was not enough, it must be backed by 
a willingness to use force. 
  Speaking at a UN Security Council session on the situation 
in 
Bosnia, U.S. Ambassador to the United Nations Madeleine Albright 
said that "it is only force plus diplomacy that can stop the 
slaughter in Sarajevo and break the stalemate in Geneva." 
  On the ten-day deadline for the withdrawal or placement 
under 
UN control of heavy weapons of the warring parties in Bosnia, 
Albright said that NATO would respond in coordination with the 
United Nations to the artillery or mortar fire that had wreaked 
the havoc in Sarajevo on February 5. 
  "These decisions are consistent with resolutions approved by 
this council," she said, and "they do not require further 
council action." 
  Observers here noted that the statement was in sharp 
contrast 
with that of her Russian counterpart Yuriy Vorontsov, who said 
at the same meeting that "the Security Council should back up 
its demands by a proper decision." 
  The U.S. ambassador also said that her government believed 
that the Bosnian conflict should be resolved at the negotiating 
table, not on the battlefield. 
  "Neither NATO, nor this council," she said, "can or should 
impose a settlement upon the parties, for an imposed settlement 
will not be a lasting settlement." 
  However, she added, by seeking to reduce the level of 
violence around Sarajevo, her government hoped to reinvigorate 
and lend substance to the negotiating process. 

</TEXT>

