<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spain To Not Join NATO Attack on Bosnian Serb Positions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1502023594 Beijing XINHUA in English 0207 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1502023594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Madrid, February 14 (XINHUA) -- Spain would not join 
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) in its possible 
air strikes against Bosnian Serb positions, Foreign Minister 
Javier Solana said today. 
  He explained that NATO, which has enough warplanes to carry 
out the air strikes, would not need Spain's participation. 
  NATO has threatened to launch air strikes against Bosnian 
Serb gun positions around Sarajevo unless the Serbs withdraw 
their weapons or surrender them to UN control by midnight GMT on 
Sunday. 
  The Bosnian Serbs were accused of launching a mortar attack 
on a Sarajevo market earlier this month. The attack, which 
killed 68 civilians and wounded nearly 200 others, led to 
renewed calls for NATO's air strikes against Bosnian Serb gun 
positions around Sarajevo. 
  Solana expressed the hope that the United Nations and NATO 
would seek an end to the Bosnian war without resorting to force. 
  He was speaking to reporters before departure for a visit to 
Andorra. 
  Solana also urged the Bosnian Serbs to withdraw their heavy 
weapons from around Sarajevo in a step "to actually lift the 
siege of the city." 
  He said he had called on the United States, France, Britain 
and Russia to help end the siege of Sarajevo through promoting 
negotiations involving the warring parties. 

</TEXT>

